<li id="cite_note-9"><b><a href="#cite_ref-9" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://www.santafe.edu/~johnson/articles.chimp.html" class="external text" title="http://www.santafe.edu/~johnson/articles.chimp.html" rel="nofollow">"Animal Language Article"</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-10"><b><a href="#cite_ref-10" title="">^</a></b> Nevertheless, recent research suggests that even weak genetic biases in speakers may, over a number of generations, influence the evolution of particular languages, leading to a non-random distribution of certain linguistic features across the world. (<a href="http://www.pnas.org/cgi/content/abstract/0610848104v1" class="external text" title="http://www.pnas.org/cgi/content/abstract/0610848104v1" rel="nofollow">Dediu, D. &amp; Ladd, D.R. (2007). Linguistic tone is related to the population frequency of the adaptive haplogroups of two brain size genes, ASPM and Microcephalin, PNAS 104:10944-10949</a>; summary available <a href="http://www.ling.ed.ac.uk/~s0340638/tonegenes/tonegenessummary.html" class="external text" title="http://www.ling.ed.ac.uk/~s0340638/tonegenes/tonegenessummary.html" rel="nofollow">here</a>)</li>
<li id="cite_note-11"><b><a href="#cite_ref-11" title="">^</a></b> <i>Much</i> is from Middle English <i>muchel</i>, which is from Proto-Germanic *<i>mekilaz</i><a href="http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=much" class="external autonumber" title="http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=much" rel="nofollow">[1]</a>, while <span lang="es" xml:lang="es"><i>mucho</i></span> is from Latin <span lang="la" xml:lang="la"><i>multus</i></span><a href="http://www.diclib.com/cgi-bin/d1.cgi?l=es&amp;base=moliner&amp;page=showid&amp;id=54702" class="external autonumber" title="http://www.diclib.com/cgi-bin/d1.cgi?l=es&amp;base=moliner&amp;page=showid&amp;id=54702" rel="nofollow">[2]</a>.</li>
<li id="cite_note-12"><b><a href="#cite_ref-12" title="">^</a></b> Chomsky, Noam. 1957. "Syntactic Structures". Mouton, The Hague</li>
<li id="cite_note-13"><b><a href="#cite_ref-13" title="">^</a></b> Carl Vogel, Ulrike Hahn, Holly Branigan 1996, "Cross serial dependencies are not hard to process", Proceedings of the 16th conference on Computational linguistics - Volume 1</li>
<li id="cite_note-Linguistic_Analysis-14">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Linguistic_Analysis_14-0" title=""><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Linguistic_Analysis_14-1" title=""><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Linguistic_Analysis_14-2" title=""><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Linguistic_Analysis_14-3" title=""><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="" id="CITEREFEades2005">Eades, Diana (2005). "<a href="http://songchau.googlepages.com/503.pdf" class="external text" title="http://songchau.googlepages.com/503.pdf" rel="nofollow">Applied Linguistics and Language Analysis in Asylum Seeker Cases</a>". <i>Applied Linguistics</i> <b>26</b> (4): 503–526. <a href="/wiki/Digital_object_identifier" title="Digital object identifier">doi</a>:<span class="neverexpand"><a href="http://dx.doi.org/10.1093%2Fapplin%2Fami021" class="external text" title="http://dx.doi.org/10.1093%2Fapplin%2Fami021" rel="nofollow">10.1093/applin/ami021</a></span><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://songchau.googlepages.com/503.pdf" class="external free" title="http://songchau.googlepages.com/503.pdf" rel="nofollow">http://songchau.googlepages.com/503.pdf</a></span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=Applied+Linguistics+and+Language+Analysis+in+Asylum+Seeker+Cases&amp;rft.jtitle=Applied+Linguistics&amp;rft.aulast=Eades&amp;rft.aufirst=Diana&amp;rft.au=Eades%2C+Diana&amp;rft.date=2005&amp;rft.volume=26&amp;rft.issue=4&amp;rft.pages=503%E2%80%93526&amp;rft_id=info:doi/10.1093%2Fapplin%2Fami021&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fsongchau.googlepages.com%2F503.pdf&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Linguistics"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
